med by the participant. Where an inconsistency is revealed, the participant must address the problem and amend the former or latter position. This also applies to inconsistent use of language terms (refer principle 7) \u8232 \u8232 2.7 Relevancy maintenance \u8232 \u8232 Maintaining reasonableness requires deliberants to maintain focus on the agreed agenda issue.\u8232 \u8232 The process should be self-enforcing. Participation entails agreement to maintain relevancy and to allow other deliberants to respectfully check or contest the relevancy of one\'92s speech move, and respectfully request a return to the agreed agenda and reasoning path. \u8232 \u8232 2.8 Information Sharing \u8232 \u8232 Factual and source information referred to by deliberants in support of their propositions or arguments should be submitted to the forum, and presented by it, for consideration by all participants. \u8232 \u8232 2.9 Argument Visualisation: Public Access Reason Display \u8232 \u8232 The reasoned contributions made by forum participants should be amalgamated onto a Web-accessible, public argument tree to convey the entire developing argument with all pro and con reasoning."\
