ened by global problems, including the recurrence of historical experiences, as per article 2.2, and (3) require global cooperation to assure their protection. \u8232 \u8232 3.3 Maintain an accessible, formal record of Universal Interests \u8232 The agreed, developing list of Universal Interests shall be maintained as a fully accessible record, a foundation for the forum\'92s constitution building process, and as a primary element of the developing constitution itself. \u8232 \u8232 3.4 Universal validity of argumentation \u8232 Participants must seek to assure that their arguments are supportive of and clearly linked to strategies that protect only those Universal Interests that have been agreed upon and formally listed by the forum. \u8232 \u8232 3.5 Impartiality \u8232 Constitutional proposals must not favour the welfare of certain groups or persons over others, nor current generations over future generations, nor adults over children. \u8232 \u8232 3.6 Generality \u8232 Constitutional proposals should apply generally, without exception or favour, and not be tied to prevailing role-players, authority figures, regimes, religions, nations, cultures, associations, traditions or persons. Principles should be formulated without reference to proper nouns. \u8232 Principles should be capable of serving in a charter of a well-ordered global society, in perpetuity. \u8232 This requires the deliberant not to participate \'91in role\'92 as an authority figure, but as one unaware of their future role. \u8232 \u8232 3.7 Reversibility \u8232 Advocates of proposals must be prepared to trade places with those likely to be most disadvantaged by the proposals. \u8232 \u8232 3.8 Acceptability of consequences of universal compliance \u8232 Advocates of proposals should consider \'96 what if everyone (globally) complied with proposals? \'96 and be able to justify the proposals in terms of the acceptability of the consequences. \u8232 \u8232 3.9 Acceptability of world system design implications \u8232 Deliberants should be prepared to consider and accept the implications of their proposals to world system design as well as to constitution of the organisation(s) to which they belong (as per principle 10)."\
